<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="43" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="42">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="43" pageId="11" pageNumber="42">
The subdivision of 
<taxonomicName family="Hypselostomatidae" lsidName="" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" rank="family">Hypselostomatidae</taxonomicName>
is strongly based on the morphology of the apertural barriers (
<normalizedToken originalValue="“teeth”">&quot;teeth&quot;</normalizedToken>
). The main characters used for delimiting some of the major genera include the formation of the two teeth on the parietal region of the aperture, namely the parietal tooth (lamella) or parietalis and the angular tooth (lamella) or angularis. 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Gyliotrachela" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gyliotrachela" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Gyliotrachela</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Paraboysidia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paraboysidia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Paraboysidia</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Acinolaemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acinolaemus" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Acinolaemus</taxonomicName>
are said to possess separate parietal and angular lamellae. The former two have a more prominent parietal lamella rather than angular lamella, but in 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Acinolaemus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acinolaemus" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Acinolaemus</taxonomicName>
, the angular is the dominant tooth. The angular lamella is entirely missing in the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Anauchen" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anauchen" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Anauchen</taxonomicName>
. In the genera 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Hypselostoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselostoma" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Hypselostoma</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Boysidia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Boysidia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Boysidia</taxonomicName>
these two lamellae are fused (
<bibRefCitation author="Pilsbry, HA" journalOrPublisher="Conchological Department, Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, Philadelphia" pageId="26" pageNumber="57" title="Manual of Conchology, Second Series: Pulmonata, Vol. 24, Pupillidae (Gastrocoptinae)" url="http://biodiversitylibrary.org/item/16727page/5/mode/1up" year="1916 - 1918">Pilsbry 1917</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Thompson, FG" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Florida Museum of Natural History, Biological Sciences" pageId="26" pageNumber="57" pagination="221 - 245" title="Vertiginid land snails from Thailand (Gastropoda, Pulmonata, Pupilloidea)." url="http://ufdc.ufl.edu/UF00095785/" volume="39" year="1997">Thompson and Upatham 1997</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation pageId="11" pageNumber="42">Panha and Burch 2005</bibRefCitation>
). Sometimes it is challenging to ascertain whether we are dealing with a single lamella (homologous with the parietal lamella) having a bifid anterior end or two lamellae (parietal and angular), which are concrescent. Moreover, the genera 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Hypselostoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselostoma" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Hypselostoma</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Gyliotrachela" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gyliotrachela" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="11" pageNumber="42" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Gyliotrachela</taxonomicName>
did not form monophyletic 
<pageBreakToken pageId="12" pageNumber="43" start="start">units</pageBreakToken>
in the molecular phylogeny presented by 
<bibRefCitation author="Tongkerd, P" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Molluscan Studies" pageId="26" pageNumber="57" pagination="139 - 147" title="Molecular phylogeny of certain Thai gastrocoptine micro land snails (Stylommatophora: Pupillidae) inferred from mitochondrial and nuclear ribosomal DNA sequences." url="10.1093/mollus/70.2.139" volume="70" year="2004">Tongkerd et al. (2004)</bibRefCitation>
, suggesting that the key characters used in classic taxonomy have developed phenotypically plastic forms. In this case of the two new species (
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Hypselostoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselostoma lacrima" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="12" pageNumber="43" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="lacrima">Hypselostoma lacrima</taxonomicName>
sp. n. and 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Hypselostoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselostoma socialis" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="12" pageNumber="43" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="socialis">Hypselostoma socialis</taxonomicName>
sp. n.), we interpret the lamella on the parietal apertural wall as a congruent angulo-parietal lamella. Hence, both species are placed in 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Hypselostoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselostoma" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="12" pageNumber="43" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Hypselostoma</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
